15039 template <typename ReferenceType, typename ThisType>
15040 static ReferenceType get_ref_impl(ThisType& obj) {
15041 // delegate the call to get_ptr<>()
15042 auto ptr = obj.template get_ptr<typename std::add_pointer<ReferenceType>::type>();
15043
15044 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(ptr != nullptr)) {
15045 return *ptr;
15046 }
15047
15048 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(303, "incompatible ReferenceType for get_ref, actual type is " +
15049 std::string(obj.type_name())));
15050 }

15074 basic_json get() const {
15075 return *this;

15139 template <typename ValueTypeCV, typename ValueType = detail::uncvref_t<ValueTypeCV>,
15140 detail::enable_if_t<not detail::is_basic_json<ValueType>::value and
15141 detail::has_from_json<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value and
15142 not detail::has_non_default_from_json<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value,
15143 int> = 0>
15144 ValueType get() const noexcept(noexcept(JSONSerializer<ValueType>::from_json(std::declval<const basic_json_t&>(),
15145 std::declval<ValueType&>()))) {
15146 // we cannot static_assert on ValueTypeCV being non-const, because
15147 // there is support for get<const basic_json_t>(), which is why we
15148 // still need the uncvref
15149 static_assert(not std::is_reference<ValueTypeCV>::value,
15150 "get() cannot be used with reference types, you might want to use get_ref()");
15151 static_assert(std::is_default_constructible<ValueType>::value,
15152 "types must be DefaultConstructible when used with get()");
15153
15154 ValueType ret;
15155 JSONSerializer<ValueType>::from_json(*this, ret);
15156 return ret;
15157 }
15158
15190 template <typename ValueTypeCV, typename ValueType = detail::uncvref_t<ValueTypeCV>,
15191 detail::enable_if_t<not std::is_same<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value and
15192 detail::has_non_default_from_json<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value,
15193 int> = 0>
15194 ValueType get() const
15195 noexcept(noexcept(JSONSerializer<ValueType>::from_json(std::declval<const basic_json_t&>()))) {
15196 static_assert(not std::is_reference<ValueTypeCV>::value,
15197 "get() cannot be used with reference types, you might want to use get_ref()");
15198 return JSONSerializer<ValueType>::from_json(*this);
15199 }

15415 template <typename ValueType,
15416 typename std::enable_if<
15417 not std::is_pointer<ValueType>::value and
15418 not std::is_same<ValueType, detail::json_ref<basic_json>>::value and
15419 not std::is_same<ValueType, typename string_t::value_type>::value and

15423 and not std::is_same<ValueType, std::initializer_list<typename string_t::value_type>>::value
15424#if defined(JSON_HAS_CPP_17) && (defined(__GNUC__) || (defined(_MSC_VER) and _MSC_VER <= 1914))

15426#endif

15429 int>::type = 0>

15431 // delegate the call to get<>() const
15432 return get<ValueType>();

15471 reference at(size_type idx) {

15473 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_array())) {
15474 JSON_TRY { return m_value.array->at(idx); }
15475 JSON_CATCH(std::out_of_range&) {
15476 // create better exception explanation
15477 JSON_THROW(out_of_range::create(401, "array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range"));
15478 }
15479 } else {
15480 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(304, "cannot use at() with " + std::string(type_name())));
15481 }

15608
15634 reference operator[](size_type idx) {
15635 // implicitly convert null value to an empty array
15636 if (is_null()) {
15637 m_type = value_t::array;
15638 m_value.array = create<array_t>();
15639 assert_invariant();
15640 }
15641
15642 // operator[] only works for arrays
15643 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_array())) {
15644 // fill up array with null values if given idx is outside range
15645 if (idx >= m_value.array->size()) {
15646 m_value.array->insert(m_value.array->end(), idx - m_value.array->size() + 1, basic_json());
15647 }
15648
15649 return m_value.array->operator[](idx);
15650 }
15651
15652 JSON_THROW(
15653 type_error::create(305, "cannot use operator[] with a numeric argument with " + std::string(type_name())));
15654 }
15655
15675 const_reference operator[](size_type idx) const {
15676 // const operator[] only works for arrays
15677 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_array())) {
15678 return m_value.array->operator[](idx);
15679 }
15680
15681 JSON_THROW(
15682 type_error::create(305, "cannot use operator[] with a numeric argument with " + std::string(type_name())));
15683 }
15684
15712 reference operator[](const typename object_t::key_type& key) {
15713 // implicitly convert null value to an empty object
15714 if (is_null()) {
15715 m_type = value_t::object;
15716 m_value.object = create<object_t>();
15717 assert_invariant();
15718 }
15719
15720 // operator[] only works for objects
15721 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_object())) {
15722 return m_value.object->operator[](key);
15723 }
15724
15725 JSON_THROW(
15726 type_error::create(305, "cannot use operator[] with a string argument with " + std::string(type_name())));
15727 }
15728
15759 const_reference operator[](const typename object_t::key_type& key) const {
15760 // const operator[] only works for objects
15761 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_object())) {
15762 assert(m_value.object->find(key) != m_value.object->end());
15763 return m_value.object->find(key)->second;
15764 }
15765
15766 JSON_THROW(
15767 type_error::create(305, "cannot use operator[] with a string argument with " + std::string(type_name())));
15768 }

15909 template <class ValueType,
15910 typename std::enable_if<std::is_convertible<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value, int>::type = 0>
15911 ValueType value(const typename object_t::key_type& key, const ValueType& default_value) const {
15912 // at only works for objects
15913 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_object())) {
15914 // if key is found, return value and given default value otherwise
15915 const auto it = find(key);
15916 if (it != end()) {
15917 return *it;
15918 }
15919
15920 return default_value;
15921 }
15922
15923 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(306, "cannot use value() with " + std::string(type_name())));
15924 }

15930 string_t value(const typename object_t::key_type& key, const char* default_value) const {
15931 return value(key, string_t(default_value));
15932 }

15977 template <class ValueType,
15978 typename std::enable_if<std::is_convertible<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value, int>::type = 0>
15979 ValueType value(const json_pointer& ptr, const ValueType& default_value) const {
15980 // at only works for objects
15981 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_object())) {
15982 // if pointer resolves a value, return it or use default value
15983 JSON_TRY { return ptr.get_checked(this); }
15984 JSON_INTERNAL_CATCH(out_of_range&) { return default_value; }
15985 }
15986
15987 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(306, "cannot use value() with " + std::string(type_name())));
15988 }

15994 JSON_HEDLEY_NON_NULL(3)
15995 string_t value(const json_pointer& ptr, const char* default_value) const {
15996 return value(ptr, string_t(default_value));
15997 }

16123 template <class IteratorType,
16124 typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
16125 std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value,
16126 int>::type = 0>
16127 IteratorType erase(IteratorType pos) {
16128 // make sure iterator fits the current value
16129 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(this != pos.m_object)) {
16130 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
16131 }
16132
16133 IteratorType result = end();
16134
16135 switch (m_type) {
16136 case value_t::boolean:
16137 case value_t::number_float:
16138 case value_t::number_integer:
16139 case value_t::number_unsigned:
16140 case value_t::string: {
16141 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not pos.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin())) {
16142 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(205, "iterator out of range"));
16143 }
16144
16145 if (is_string()) {
16146 AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
16147 std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::destroy(alloc, m_value.string);
16148 std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::deallocate(alloc, m_value.string, 1);
16149 m_value.string = nullptr;
16150 }
16151
16152 m_type = value_t::null;
16153 assert_invariant();
16154 break;
16155 }
16156
16157 case value_t::object: {
16158 result.m_it.object_iterator = m_value.object->erase(pos.m_it.object_iterator);
16159 break;
16160 }
16161
16162 case value_t::array: {
16163 result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->erase(pos.m_it.array_iterator);
16164 break;
16165 }
16166
16167 default:
16168 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(307, "cannot use erase() with " + std::string(type_name())));
16169 }
16170
16171 return result;
16172 }
16173
16220 template <class IteratorType,
16221 typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
16222 std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value,
16223 int>::type = 0>
16224 IteratorType erase(IteratorType first, IteratorType last) {
16225 // make sure iterator fits the current value
16226 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(this != first.m_object or this != last.m_object)) {
16227 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(203, "iterators do not fit current value"));
16228 }
16229
16230 IteratorType result = end();
16231
16232 switch (m_type) {
16233 case value_t::boolean:
16234 case value_t::number_float:
16235 case value_t::number_integer:
16236 case value_t::number_unsigned:
16237 case value_t::string: {
16238 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(not first.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin() or
16239 not last.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_end())) {
16240 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(204, "iterators out of range"));
16241 }
16242
16243 if (is_string()) {
16244 AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
16245 std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::destroy(alloc, m_value.string);
16246 std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::deallocate(alloc, m_value.string, 1);
16247 m_value.string = nullptr;
16248 }
16249
16250 m_type = value_t::null;
16251 assert_invariant();
16252 break;
16253 }
16254
16255 case value_t::object: {
16256 result.m_it.object_iterator = m_value.object->erase(first.m_it.object_iterator, last.m_it.object_iterator);
16257 break;
16258 }
16259
16260 case value_t::array: {
16261 result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->erase(first.m_it.array_iterator, last.m_it.array_iterator);
16262 break;
16263 }
16264
16265 default:
16266 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(307, "cannot use erase() with " + std::string(type_name())));
16267 }
16268
16269 return result;
16270 }

16301 size_type erase(const typename object_t::key_type& key) {
16302 // this erase only works for objects
16303 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_object())) {
16304 return m_value.object->erase(key);
16305 }
16306
16307 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(307, "cannot use erase() with " + std::string(type_name())));
16308 }
16309
16334 void erase(const size_type idx) {
16335 // this erase only works for arrays
16336 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_array())) {
16337 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(idx >= size())) {
16338 JSON_THROW(out_of_range::create(401, "array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range"));
16339 }
16340
16341 m_value.array->erase(m_value.array->begin() + static_cast<difference_type>(idx));
16342 } else {
16343 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(307, "cannot use erase() with " + std::string(type_name())));
16344 }
16345 }

16535
16561 const_iterator cbegin() const noexcept {
16562 const_iterator result(this);

16891
16933 bool empty() const noexcept {
16934 switch (m_type) {
16935 case value_t::null: {
16936 // null values are empty
16937 return true;
16938 }
16939
16940 case value_t::array: {
16941 // delegate call to array_t::empty()
16942 return m_value.array->empty();
16943 }
16944
16945 case value_t::object: {
16946 // delegate call to object_t::empty()
16947 return m_value.object->empty();
16948 }
16949
16950 default: {
16951 // all other types are nonempty
16952 return false;
16953 }
16954 }
16955 }
16956
16999 size_type size() const noexcept {
17000 switch (m_type) {
17001 case value_t::null: {
17002 // null values are empty
17003 return 0;
17004 }
17005
17006 case value_t::array: {
17007 // delegate call to array_t::size()
17008 return m_value.array->size();
17009 }
17010
17011 case value_t::object: {
17012 // delegate call to object_t::size()
17013 return m_value.object->size();
17014 }
17015
17016 default: {
17017 // all other types have size 1
17018 return 1;
17019 }
17020 }
17021 }
17022
17063 size_type max_size() const noexcept {
17064 switch (m_type) {
17065 case value_t::array: {
17066 // delegate call to array_t::max_size()
17067 return m_value.array->max_size();
17068 }
17069
17070 case value_t::object: {
17071 // delegate call to object_t::max_size()
17072 return m_value.object->max_size();
17073 }
17074
17075 default: {
17076 // all other types have max_size() == size()
17077 return size();
17078 }
17079 }
17080 }

17127 void clear() noexcept {
17128 switch (m_type) {
17129 case value_t::number_integer: {
17130 m_value.number_integer = 0;
17131 break;
17132 }
17133
17134 case value_t::number_unsigned: {
17135 m_value.number_unsigned = 0;
17136 break;
17137 }
17138
17139 case value_t::number_float: {
17140 m_value.number_float = 0.0;
17141 break;
17142 }
17143
17144 case value_t::boolean: {
17145 m_value.boolean = false;
17146 break;
17147 }
17148
17149 case value_t::string: {
17150 m_value.string->clear();
17151 break;
17152 }
17153
17154 case value_t::array: {
17155 m_value.array->clear();
17156 break;
17157 }
17158
17159 case value_t::object: {
17160 m_value.object->clear();
17161 break;
17162 }
17163
17164 default:
17165 break;
17166 }

17168
17189 void push_back(basic_json&& val) {
17190 // push_back only works for null objects or arrays
17191 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array()))) {
17192 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(308, "cannot use push_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17193 }
17194
17195 // transform null object into an array
17196 if (is_null()) {
17197 m_type = value_t::array;
17198 m_value = value_t::array;
17199 assert_invariant();
17200 }
17201
17202 // add element to array (move semantics)
17203 m_value.array->push_back(std::move(val));
17204 // invalidate object: mark it null so we do not call the destructor
17205 // cppcheck-suppress accessMoved
17206 val.m_type = value_t::null;
17207 }
17208
17213 reference operator+=(basic_json&& val) {
17214 push_back(std::move(val));
17215 return *this;
17216 }
17217
17222 void push_back(const basic_json& val) {
17223 // push_back only works for null objects or arrays
17224 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array()))) {
17225 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(308, "cannot use push_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17226 }
17227
17228 // transform null object into an array
17229 if (is_null()) {
17230 m_type = value_t::array;
17231 m_value = value_t::array;
17232 assert_invariant();
17233 }
17234
17235 // add element to array
17236 m_value.array->push_back(val);
17237 }
17238
17243 reference operator+=(const basic_json& val) {
17244 push_back(val);
17245 return *this;
17246 }
17247
17268 void push_back(const typename object_t::value_type& val) {
17269 // push_back only works for null objects or objects
17270 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_object()))) {
17271 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(308, "cannot use push_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17272 }
17273
17274 // transform null object into an object
17275 if (is_null()) {
17276 m_type = value_t::object;
17277 m_value = value_t::object;
17278 assert_invariant();
17279 }
17280
17281 // add element to array
17282 m_value.object->insert(val);
17283 }
17284
17289 reference operator+=(const typename object_t::value_type& val) {
17290 push_back(val);
17291 return *this;
17292 }
17293
17319 void push_back(initializer_list_t init) {
17320 if (is_object() and init.size() == 2 and (*init.begin())->is_string()) {
17321 basic_json&& key = init.begin()->moved_or_copied();
17322 push_back(typename object_t::value_type(std::move(key.get_ref<string_t&>()),
17323 (init.begin() + 1)->moved_or_copied()));
17324 } else {
17325 push_back(basic_json(init));
17326 }
17327 }
17328
17333 reference operator+=(initializer_list_t init) {
17334 push_back(init);
17335 return *this;
17336 }
17337
17361 template <class... Args>
17362 reference emplace_back(Args&&... args) {
17363 // emplace_back only works for null objects or arrays
17364 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array()))) {
17365 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(311, "cannot use emplace_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17366 }
17367
17368 // transform null object into an array
17369 if (is_null()) {
17370 m_type = value_t::array;
17371 m_value = value_t::array;
17372 assert_invariant();
17373 }
17374
17375// add element to array (perfect forwarding)
17376#ifdef JSON_HAS_CPP_17
17377 return m_value.array->emplace_back(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
17378#else
17379 m_value.array->emplace_back(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
17380 return m_value.array->back();
17381#endif
17382 }
17383
17411 template <class... Args>
17412 std::pair<iterator, bool> emplace(Args&&... args) {
17413 // emplace only works for null objects or arrays
17414 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_object()))) {
17415 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(311, "cannot use emplace() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17416 }
17417
17418 // transform null object into an object
17419 if (is_null()) {
17420 m_type = value_t::object;
17421 m_value = value_t::object;
17422 assert_invariant();
17423 }
17424
17425 // add element to array (perfect forwarding)
17426 auto res = m_value.object->emplace(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
17427 // create result iterator and set iterator to the result of emplace
17428 auto it = begin();
17429 it.m_it.object_iterator = res.first;
17430
17431 // return pair of iterator and boolean
17432 return {it, res.second};
17433 }
17434
17438 template <typename... Args>
17439 iterator insert_iterator(const_iterator pos, Args&&... args) {
17440 iterator result(this);
17441 assert(m_value.array != nullptr);
17442
17443 auto insert_pos = std::distance(m_value.array->begin(), pos.m_it.array_iterator);
17444 m_value.array->insert(pos.m_it.array_iterator, std::forward<Args>(args)...);
17445 result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->begin() + insert_pos;
17446
17447 // This could have been written as:
17448 // result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->insert(pos.m_it.array_iterator, cnt, val);
17449 // but the return value of insert is missing in GCC 4.8, so it is written this way instead.
17450
17451 return result;
17452 }
17453
17476 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, const basic_json& val) {
17477 // insert only works for arrays
17478 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_array())) {
17479 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
17480 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this)) {
17481 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
17482 }
17483
17484 // insert to array and return iterator
17485 return insert_iterator(pos, val);
17486 }
17487
17488 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17489 }
17490
17495 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, basic_json&& val) { return insert(pos, val); }
17496
17521 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, size_type cnt, const basic_json& val) {
17522 // insert only works for arrays
17523 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(is_array())) {
17524 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
17525 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this)) {
17526 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
17527 }
17528
17529 // insert to array and return iterator
17530 return insert_iterator(pos, cnt, val);
17531 }
17532
17533 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17534 }
17535
17566 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, const_iterator first, const_iterator last) {
17567 // insert only works for arrays
17568 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not is_array())) {
17569 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17570 }
17571
17572 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
17573 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this)) {
17574 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
17575 }
17576
17577 // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
17578 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object)) {
17579 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
17580 }
17581
17582 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(first.m_object == this)) {
17583 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(211, "passed iterators may not belong to container"));
17584 }
17585
17586 // insert to array and return iterator
17587 return insert_iterator(pos, first.m_it.array_iterator, last.m_it.array_iterator);
17588 }
17589
17614 iterator insert(const_iterator pos, initializer_list_t ilist) {
17615 // insert only works for arrays
17616 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not is_array())) {
17617 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17618 }
17619
17620 // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
17621 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this)) {
17622 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
17623 }
17624
17625 // insert to array and return iterator
17626 return insert_iterator(pos, ilist.begin(), ilist.end());
17627 }
17628
17652 void insert(const_iterator first, const_iterator last) {
17653 // insert only works for objects
17654 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not is_object())) {
17655 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17656 }
17657
17658 // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
17659 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object)) {
17660 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
17661 }
17662
17663 // passed iterators must belong to objects
17664 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not first.m_object->is_object())) {
17665 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterators first and last must point to objects"));
17666 }
17667
17668 m_value.object->insert(first.m_it.object_iterator, last.m_it.object_iterator);
17669 }
17670
17690 void update(const_reference j) {
17691 // implicitly convert null value to an empty object
17692 if (is_null()) {
17693 m_type = value_t::object;
17694 m_value.object = create<object_t>();
17695 assert_invariant();
17696 }
17697
17698 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not is_object())) {
17699 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17700 }
17701 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not j.is_object())) {
17702 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(j.type_name())));
17703 }
17704
17705 for (auto it = j.cbegin(); it != j.cend(); ++it) {
17706 m_value.object->operator[](it.key()) = it.value();
17707 }
17708 }
17709
17736 void update(const_iterator first, const_iterator last) {
17737 // implicitly convert null value to an empty object
17738 if (is_null()) {
17739 m_type = value_t::object;
17740 m_value.object = create<object_t>();
17741 assert_invariant();
17742 }
17743
17744 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not is_object())) {
17745 JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(type_name())));
17746 }
17747
17748 // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
17749 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object)) {
17750 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
17751 }
17752
17753 // passed iterators must belong to objects
17754 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not first.m_object->is_object() or not last.m_object->is_object())) {
17755 JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterators first and last must point to objects"));
17756 }
17757
17758 for (auto it = first; it != last; ++it) {
17759 m_value.object->operator[](it.key()) = it.value();
17760 }
17761 }

17880 // lexicographical comparison operators //
17882
17885
17926 friend bool operator==(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept {
17927 const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
17928 const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
17929
17930 if (lhs_type == rhs_type) {
17931 switch (lhs_type) {
17932 case value_t::array:
17933 return *lhs.m_value.array == *rhs.m_value.array;
17934
17935 case value_t::object:
17936 return *lhs.m_value.object == *rhs.m_value.object;
17937
17938 case value_t::null:
17939 return true;
17940
17941 case value_t::string:
17942 return *lhs.m_value.string == *rhs.m_value.string;
17943
17944 case value_t::boolean:
17945 return lhs.m_value.boolean == rhs.m_value.boolean;
17946
17947 case value_t::number_integer:
17948 return lhs.m_value.number_integer == rhs.m_value.number_integer;
17949
17950 case value_t::number_unsigned:
17951 return lhs.m_value.number_unsigned == rhs.m_value.number_unsigned;
17952
17953 case value_t::number_float:
17954 return lhs.m_value.number_float == rhs.m_value.number_float;
17955
17956 default:
17957 return false;
17958 }
17959 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
17960 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) == rhs.m_value.number_float;
17961 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
17962 return lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer);
17963 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
17964 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_float;
17965 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
17966 return lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
17967 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
17968 return static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_integer;
17969 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
17970 return lhs.m_value.number_integer == static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
17971 }
17972
17973 return false;
17974 }

18031
18058 friend bool operator<(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept {
18059 const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
18060 const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
18061
18062 if (lhs_type == rhs_type) {
18063 switch (lhs_type) {
18064 case value_t::array:
18065 // note parentheses are necessary, see
18066 // https://github.com/nlohmann/json/issues/1530
18067 return (*lhs.m_value.array) < (*rhs.m_value.array);
18068
18069 case value_t::object:
18070 return (*lhs.m_value.object) < (*rhs.m_value.object);
18071
18072 case value_t::null:
18073 return false;
18074
18075 case value_t::string:
18076 return (*lhs.m_value.string) < (*rhs.m_value.string);
18077
18078 case value_t::boolean:
18079 return (lhs.m_value.boolean) < (rhs.m_value.boolean);
18080
18081 case value_t::number_integer:
18082 return (lhs.m_value.number_integer) < (rhs.m_value.number_integer);
18083
18084 case value_t::number_unsigned:
18085 return (lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < (rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
18086
18087 case value_t::number_float:
18088 return (lhs.m_value.number_float) < (rhs.m_value.number_float);
18089
18090 default:
18091 return false;
18092 }
18093 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
18094 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
18095 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
18096 return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer);
18097 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
18098 return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
18099 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
18100 return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
18101 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
18102 return lhs.m_value.number_integer < static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
18103 } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
18104 return static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_integer;
18105 }
18106
18107 // We only reach this line if we cannot compare values. In that case,
18108 // we compare types. Note we have to call the operator explicitly,
18109 // because MSVC has problems otherwise.
18110 return operator<(lhs_type, rhs_type);
18111 }
18112
18117 template <typename ScalarType, typename std::enable_if<std::is_scalar<ScalarType>::value, int>::type = 0>
18118 friend bool operator<(const_reference lhs, const ScalarType rhs) noexcept {
18119 return lhs < basic_json(rhs);
18120 }
18121
18126 template <typename ScalarType, typename std::enable_if<std::is_scalar<ScalarType>::value, int>::type = 0>
18127 friend bool operator<(const ScalarType lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept {

18294 o.width(0);

18296 // do the actual serialization
18297 serializer s(detail::output_adapter<char>(o), o.fill());
18298 s.dump(j, pretty_print, false, static_cast<unsigned int>(indentation));
18299 return o;

18615 JSON_HEDLEY_RETURNS_NON_NULL
18616 const char* type_name() const noexcept {
18617 {
18618 switch (m_type) {
18619 case value_t::null:
18620 return "null";
18621 case value_t::object:
18622 return "object";
18623 case value_t::array:
18624 return "array";
18625 case value_t::string:
18626 return "string";
18627 case value_t::boolean:
18628 return "boolean";
18629 case value_t::discarded:
18630 return "discarded";
18631 default:
18632 return "number";
18633 }

19627
19629 // JSON Patch functions //
19631
19634
19682 basic_json patch(const basic_json& json_patch) const {
19683 // make a working copy to apply the patch to
19684 basic_json result = *this;
19685
19686 // the valid JSON Patch operations
19687 enum class patch_operations { add, remove, replace, move, copy, test, invalid };
19688
19689 const auto get_op = [](const std::string& op) {
19690 if (op == "add") {
19691 return patch_operations::add;
19692 }
19693 if (op == "remove") {
19694 return patch_operations::remove;
19695 }
19696 if (op == "replace") {
19697 return patch_operations::replace;
19698 }
19699 if (op == "move") {
19700 return patch_operations::move;
19701 }
19702 if (op == "copy") {
19703 return patch_operations::copy;
19704 }
19705 if (op == "test") {
19706 return patch_operations::test;
19707 }
19708
19709 return patch_operations::invalid;
19710 };
19711
19712 // wrapper for "add" operation; add value at ptr
19713 const auto operation_add = [&result](json_pointer& ptr, basic_json val) {
19714 // adding to the root of the target document means replacing it
19715 if (ptr.empty()) {
19716 result = val;
19717 return;
19718 }
19719
19720 // make sure the top element of the pointer exists
19721 json_pointer top_pointer = ptr.top();
19722 if (top_pointer != ptr) {
19723 result.at(top_pointer);
19724 }
19725
19726 // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
19727 const auto last_path = ptr.back();
19728 ptr.pop_back();
19729 basic_json& parent = result[ptr];
19730
19731 switch (parent.m_type) {
19732 case value_t::null:
19733 case value_t::object: {
19734 // use operator[] to add value
19735 parent[last_path] = val;
19736 break;
19737 }
19738
19739 case value_t::array: {
19740 if (last_path == "-") {
19741 // special case: append to back
19742 parent.push_back(val);
19743 } else {
19744 const auto idx = json_pointer::array_index(last_path);
19745 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(static_cast<size_type>(idx) > parent.size())) {
19746 // avoid undefined behavior
19747 JSON_THROW(
19748 out_of_range::create(401, "array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range"));
19749 }
19750
19751 // default case: insert add offset
19752 parent.insert(parent.begin() + static_cast<difference_type>(idx), val);
19753 }
19754 break;
19755 }
19756
19757 // if there exists a parent it cannot be primitive
19758 default: // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
19759 assert(false); // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
19760 }
19761 };
19762
19763 // wrapper for "remove" operation; remove value at ptr
19764 const auto operation_remove = [&result](json_pointer& ptr) {
19765 // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
19766 const auto last_path = ptr.back();
19767 ptr.pop_back();
19768 basic_json& parent = result.at(ptr);
19769
19770 // remove child
19771 if (parent.is_object()) {
19772 // perform range check
19773 auto it = parent.find(last_path);
19774 if (JSON_HEDLEY_LIKELY(it != parent.end())) {
19775 parent.erase(it);
19776 } else {
19777 JSON_THROW(out_of_range::create(403, "key '" + last_path + "' not found"));
19778 }
19779 } else if (parent.is_array()) {
19780 // note erase performs range check
19781 parent.erase(static_cast<size_type>(json_pointer::array_index(last_path)));
19782 }
19783 };
19784
19785 // type check: top level value must be an array
19786 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not json_patch.is_array())) {
19787 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(104, 0, "JSON patch must be an array of objects"));
19788 }
19789
19790 // iterate and apply the operations
19791 for (const auto& val : json_patch) {
19792 // wrapper to get a value for an operation
19793 const auto get_value = [&val](const std::string& op, const std::string& member,
19794 bool string_type) -> basic_json& {
19795 // find value
19796 auto it = val.m_value.object->find(member);
19797
19798 // context-sensitive error message
19799 const auto error_msg = (op == "op") ? "operation" : "operation '" + op + "'";
19800
19801 // check if desired value is present
19802 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(it == val.m_value.object->end())) {
19803 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, error_msg + " must have member '" + member + "'"));
19804 }
19805
19806 // check if result is of type string
19807 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(string_type and not it->second.is_string())) {
19808 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, error_msg + " must have string member '" + member + "'"));
19809 }
19810
19811 // no error: return value
19812 return it->second;
19813 };
19814
19815 // type check: every element of the array must be an object
19816 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not val.is_object())) {
19817 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(104, 0, "JSON patch must be an array of objects"));
19818 }
19819
19820 // collect mandatory members
19821 const std::string op = get_value("op", "op", true);
19822 const std::string path = get_value(op, "path", true);
19823 json_pointer ptr(path);
19824
19825 switch (get_op(op)) {
19826 case patch_operations::add: {
19827 operation_add(ptr, get_value("add", "value", false));
19828 break;
19829 }
19830
19831 case patch_operations::remove: {
19832 operation_remove(ptr);
19833 break;
19834 }
19835
19836 case patch_operations::replace: {
19837 // the "path" location must exist - use at()
19838 result.at(ptr) = get_value("replace", "value", false);
19839 break;
19840 }
19841
19842 case patch_operations::move: {
19843 const std::string from_path = get_value("move", "from", true);
19844 json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
19845
19846 // the "from" location must exist - use at()
19847 basic_json v = result.at(from_ptr);
19848
19849 // The move operation is functionally identical to a
19850 // "remove" operation on the "from" location, followed
19851 // immediately by an "add" operation at the target
19852 // location with the value that was just removed.
19853 operation_remove(from_ptr);
19854 operation_add(ptr, v);
19855 break;
19856 }
19857
19858 case patch_operations::copy: {
19859 const std::string from_path = get_value("copy", "from", true);
19860 const json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
19861
19862 // the "from" location must exist - use at()
19863 basic_json v = result.at(from_ptr);
19864
19865 // The copy is functionally identical to an "add"
19866 // operation at the target location using the value
19867 // specified in the "from" member.
19868 operation_add(ptr, v);
19869 break;
19870 }
19871
19872 case patch_operations::test: {
19873 bool success = false;
19874 JSON_TRY {
19875 // check if "value" matches the one at "path"
19876 // the "path" location must exist - use at()
19877 success = (result.at(ptr) == get_value("test", "value", false));
19878 }
19879 JSON_INTERNAL_CATCH(out_of_range&) {
19880 // ignore out of range errors: success remains false
19881 }
19882
19883 // throw an exception if test fails
19884 if (JSON_HEDLEY_UNLIKELY(not success)) {
19885 JSON_THROW(other_error::create(501, "unsuccessful: " + val.dump()));
19886 }
19887
19888 break;
19889 }
19890
19891 default: {
19892 // op must be "add", "remove", "replace", "move", "copy", or
19893 // "test"
19894 JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, "operation value '" + op + "' is invalid"));
19895 }
19896 }
19897 }
19898
19899 return result;
19900 }
19901
19935 JSON_HEDLEY_WARN_UNUSED_RESULT
19936 static basic_json diff(const basic_json& source, const basic_json& target, const std::string& path = "") {
19937 // the patch
19938 basic_json result(value_t::array);
19939
19940 // if the values are the same, return empty patch
19941 if (source == target) {
19942 return result;
19943 }
19944
19945 if (source.type() != target.type()) {
19946 // different types: replace value
19947 result.push_back({{"op", "replace"}, {"path", path}, {"value", target}});
19948 return result;
19949 }
19950
19951 switch (source.type()) {
19952 case value_t::array: {
19953 // first pass: traverse common elements
19954 std::size_t i = 0;
19955 while (i < source.size() and i < target.size()) {
19956 // recursive call to compare array values at index i
19957 auto temp_diff = diff(source[i], target[i], path + "/" + std::to_string(i));
19958 result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
19959 ++i;
19960 }
19961
19962 // i now reached the end of at least one array
19963 // in a second pass, traverse the remaining elements
19964
19965 // remove my remaining elements
19966 const auto end_index = static_cast<difference_type>(result.size());
19967 while (i < source.size()) {
19968 // add operations in reverse order to avoid invalid
19969 // indices
19970 result.insert(result.begin() + end_index,
19971 object({{"op", "remove"}, {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)}}));
19972 ++i;
19973 }
19974
19975 // add other remaining elements
19976 while (i < target.size()) {
19977 result.push_back({{"op", "add"}, {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)}, {"value", target[i]}});
19978 ++i;
19979 }
19980
19981 break;
19982 }
19983
19984 case value_t::object: {
19985 // first pass: traverse this object's elements
19986 for (auto it = source.cbegin(); it != source.cend(); ++it) {
19987 // escape the key name to be used in a JSON patch
19988 const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
19989
19990 if (target.find(it.key()) != target.end()) {
19991 // recursive call to compare object values at key it
19992 auto temp_diff = diff(it.value(), target[it.key()], path + "/" + key);
19993 result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
19994 } else {
19995 // found a key that is not in o -> remove it
19996 result.push_back(object({{"op", "remove"}, {"path", path + "/" + key}}));
19997 }
19998 }
19999
20000 // second pass: traverse other object's elements
20001 for (auto it = target.cbegin(); it != target.cend(); ++it) {
20002 if (source.find(it.key()) == source.end()) {
20003 // found a key that is not in this -> add it
20004 const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
20005 result.push_back({{"op", "add"}, {"path", path + "/" + key}, {"value", it.value()}});
20006 }
20007 }
20008
20009 break;
20010 }
20011
20012 default: {
20013 // both primitive type: replace value
20014 result.push_back({{"op", "replace"}, {"path", path}, {"value", target}});
20015 break;
20016 }
20017 }
20018
20019 return result;
20020 }
20021
20023
20025 // JSON Merge Patch functions //
20027
20030
20073 void merge_patch(const basic_json& apply_patch) {
20074 if (apply_patch.is_object()) {
20075 if (not is_object()) {
20076 *this = object();
20077 }
20078 for (auto it = apply_patch.begin(); it != apply_patch.end(); ++it) {
20079 if (it.value().is_null()) {
20080 erase(it.key());
20081 } else {
20082 operator[](it.key()).merge_patch(it.value());
20083 }
20084 }
20085 } else {
20086 *this = apply_patch;
20087 }
20088 }
20089
20091};
